data.content:
Yes — the direct cast `(EmailHandler)result` throws an `InvalidCastException` on failure, not a clear test assertion. Use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType`, which gives a proper test failure message:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler));
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

Or with the generic overload (MSTest v2.2.8+):

```csharp
var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
```

The generic version is the cleanest — it asserts the type **and** returns the typed reference in one call, so you can keep testing properties without a separate cast.
